# Claude Code as a GitHub App: Setup & Auth

Goal: Claude Code authenticates to GitHub as a dedicated GitHub App identity,
not as you. Commits, pushes, PRs, and issue comments are attributed to the App.
Your personal `~/.gitconfig` is left alone.

This doc covers a GitHub Teams org. Same procedure works on Free/Pro/Enterprise;
only the org-level UI paths differ slightly.

---

## 1. Register the GitHub App

In the org that owns the repos:

Go to **Org settings → Developer settings → GitHub Apps → New GitHub
App**.

Fill in:

- **Name**: e.g. `claude-bot` (must be globally unique across GitHub; pick
  something org-scoped if needed, like `example-claude-app`)
- **Homepage URL**: anything; your org URL is fine
- **Webhook**: uncheck **Active** — you don't need webhooks for local Claude
  Code usage
- **Repository permissions** (starter set):
  - Contents: **Read & write**
  - Pull requests: **Read & write**
  - Issues: **Read & write**
  - Metadata: **Read** (auto-selected)
  - Checks: **Read** (lets Claude see CI status)
  - Workflows: **Read & write** *only if* you want Claude to modify files under
    `.github/workflows/`
- **Where can this GitHub App be installed?**: **Only on this account**

Create the App.

After creation, on the App's settings page note:

- **App ID** (numeric, top of the page)
- **Slug** (from the URL:
  `https://github.com/organizations/<org>/settings/apps/<slug>`)

Then:

- **Generate a private key** → downloads a `.pem` file. Store it somewhere safe;
  you cannot re-download it.
- Optionally rotate/regenerate later from this same page.

---

## 2. Install the App on your repos

Still on the App's settings page: **Install App** (left nav) → choose your org →
**Only select repositories** → pick the repos Claude should work on.

After install, note the **Installation ID**. Easiest way: the install URL ends
with `/installations/<id>`. Or query it later with the API.

---

## 3. Identify the App's bot identity

GitHub assigns every App a synthetic user with this email format:

```text
<APP_ID>+<SLUG>[bot]@users.noreply.github.com
```

Example: App ID `1234567`, slug `claude-bot` →

```text
1234567+claude-bot[bot]@users.noreply.github.com
```

**This exact format is what makes GitHub attribute commits to the bot account
with the `[bot]` badge.** Any other email and GitHub will just show the literal
string.

The matching display name convention is `claude-bot[bot]`.

**This bot email doubles as the "is this an App repo?" signal.** The
local-config setup in §5 sets `user.email` to exactly this string. The
PreToolUse hook in §7.2 keys its naked-`gh` deny on
`git config --local user.email` matching
`*[bot]@users.noreply.github.com`. So the same value that earns the
commit badge is what tells the hook this repo is App-managed. Keep them
in lockstep: a repo is "App-configured" iff its local `user.email` is
the bot address.

