## 7. Telling Claude Code to use this

Claude Code shells out to `git` and inherits the repo's `.git/config`. Once §5
is done in a given repo, **`git` commits and pushes use the bot identity
automatically** — no Claude-Code-specific configuration needed, because the
credential helper (§4.3) mints a fresh token on every git operation.

`gh` and direct REST/GraphQL calls are different: they don't go through the git
credential helper, so they need their own fresh-token path. An `export
GITHUB_TOKEN=$(get-token.sh)` is evaluated once and goes **stale after ~1 hour**
— a long Claude session would start getting 401s mid-run. The fix is a wrapper
that re-mints per call.

### 7.1 `gh_wrapper` (ships in this repo → `~/.claude/bin/gh_wrapper`)

This wrapper re-mints `GH_TOKEN` on every call (the cache script only hits the
network when the token is within 5 min of expiry, so the common case is a cheap
`jq`/`date` check). It **falls through to real `gh`** when the App isn't set up
on this machine, so it is safe to ship to every machine via the `~/.claude`
mirror.

`bin/gh_wrapper` in this repo (→ `~/.claude/bin/gh_wrapper`):

```bash
#!/usr/bin/env bash
# Run `gh` as the Claude GitHub App identity by minting a fresh
# installation token per call. Falls through to plain `gh` when the
# App identity isn't configured on this machine.
set -euo pipefail
TOKEN_SCRIPT="$HOME/.config/claude-github-app/get-token.sh"
if [[ -x "$TOKEN_SCRIPT" ]]; then
  GH_TOKEN="$("$TOKEN_SCRIPT")" exec gh "$@"
else
  exec gh "$@"
fi
```

`GH_TOKEN` takes precedence over any stored `gh auth login` credentials, so no
`gh auth logout` is needed. For direct `curl` against the API, mint inline
rather than exporting a stale token:

```bash
curl -H "Authorization: Bearer $(~/.config/claude-github-app/get-token.sh)" ...
```

### 7.2 Enforcing the wrapper via the PreToolUse hook

Naked `gh` is dangerous precisely because it fails *silently* into the wrong
identity: if the App token isn't on the environment, `gh` uses your personal `gh
auth login` credentials and the action is attributed to you, with no error. To
prevent that in headless/subagent runs, the PreToolUse Bash hook
(`hooks/auto-approve-compound-commands.sh`) denies a bare `gh` invocation **only
when the current repo is App-configured** (local `user.email` matches
`*[bot]@users.noreply.github.com`, per §3), with a `permissionDecisionReason`
instructing the agent to use `gh_wrapper`. The agent's self-correction loop then
retries correctly — the same mechanism the existing `cd <path> &&` / `git -C`
denies use.

Notes:

- The deny fires on `PreToolUse` only (headless/subagent). Interactive
  `PermissionRequest` sessions fall through to a normal prompt — the harness
  can't take a deny verdict there. This is acceptable: the silent-wrong-identity
  risk is highest in unattended subagent runs.
- In non-App repos and on machines with no App configured, naked `gh` is correct
  and is **not** denied.
- This hook rule is **not yet implemented** — see the implementation checklist
  in §10.

